Analysis on Relationship Quality Amongst Couples

Ryan Brady

May 2, 2016

In this data set we see the results of 3000 couples, from the years 2009-2015, who reported on their current relationship. This report mainly explores the factors which cause people to break up. Different variables, such as parental approval and a persons self reported relationship status, are studied to help see whether a couple would break up or not. Many times in this report, generalized linear models are used in study how certain predictor variables affect a persons probability of breaking up with their current partner or getting married.

In this data set there are many different varibales to explore. Numerical variables detail specific continuous random variables. Three examples in the data set are age, partners age, and years met. Each of these variables are quantified by a numeric value. An example of three categorical variables include race, gender attraction, and religion. Three different types of ordinal data are income,degrees seperation, and relationship quality.

In both the ordinal data specified above and categorical data there are examples of binning variables. In the ordinal data, income is ranked by which income class a person is in, and for categorical data, race and religion both have binned categories, for race the category hispanic groups all different people of latino descent and for religion, there are categories, Other Christian and Other Non-Christian, that bin many different sects of religion into one bloc.

Below lies the demographics of the subjects.

From these graphs it is of note that almost 80 percent of people surveyed were white and that the rest of the minorities only make up 20 percent of the data. This is significantly different than the distribution of ethinicities in America where only 63 percent of the population is non-hispanic white. This clearly suggests that the results will show bias towards White Americans.

The proportion of couples that broke up after the survey was first conducted is 18.8 percent of the total amount of couples surveyed. The proportion of couples that were orriginally surveyed and eventually got married is 21.5 percent. Nine subjects got married and broke up between the time the first survey was asked and the follow up survey was conducted. These eight people tended to have a few things in common, such as eight of them lived in a metropolitan area, eight of them owned their own residence, they were all from some sect of Christianity, and seven of them had thirteen years of education. Also seven of the people described their relationship quality as excellent and the other two both defined their relationships as good. From these facts it seems that possibly living in a metropolitan area may make relationships more hectic and have a higher likelihood of a stronger breakup.

To see if there is a connection between couples and age of subject and age of subjects parter a generalized linear model is fit. Below, the table illustrates that while the subjects age seems to have a negligible affect on whether a couple breaks up or not, the partners age suggests that for every year a partner increases in age, the odds that the couple breaks up is 0.95 times as likely.

Now to see if there is a connection between the age of a relationship and whether a couple breaks up, another generalized linear model is fit. From the table below, for every year a couple stays together the odds they break up is multiplied by 0.892. Therefore the length of a couples relationship does have a profound affect on whether or not the couple gets a divorce.

The first graphic of part five illustrates the frequency of difference of age in couples amongst the couples surveyed. It notes that a significant majority of partners are within 10 years in age of one another.

The next plot explores the difference in ages amongst heterosexual couples; the formula is male age minues female age. The graph notes an approximately normal distribution with a slight skew to the left. Hence, the median is two and mean 2.278, this highlights that males are more likely to be older than their female parter, and on average they are about two years older than their female partner.

The first table of Part 6 suggests that the odds that a couple, where both partners come from the same hometown, breaks up is .86 times that of a couple where both partners come from differing hometowns. This suggests that couples where both partners are from the same hometown is more likely to stay together than a couple which both partners come from different hometowns.

This next table notes the amount of breakups for people with the same religions and people with different religions. Thus we see that the odds people with different religions break up is 1.796 of that of couples who share a religion. Also of note is that 24 percent of couples with different religions will break up while only 13 percent of couples with the same religion will break up.

The final table of part 6 looks to see if there is a relationship between the difference in education of partners and whether that influences a couple to break up or not. To do this a generalized linear model is fit to see if breakups are influenced by a difference in education. From the table though it appears the the difference in a single year of education is not actually a significant predictor of whether or not a couple breaks up.

In part 7, the first table that appears denotes self reported relationship quality, and whether that partner broke up with his or her partner. In this table it is apparent that in very poor relationships or poor relationships, couples broke up 52.8 percent of the time, compared to that of people in good or excellent relationships only broke up only 15 percent of the time. Thus the odds someone breaks up that is in either a very poor or poor relationship is 3.35 times that of someone in a good or excellent relationship.

In the next table, relationship quality versus amount of children is explored to see if there is a relationship between how self reported relationship quality influences a couples likelihood of having multiple kids.

From the Mosaic plot below it does not seem that the amount of children is indicated by relationship quality. However, it does not appear that relationship quality seems to have an affect on whether a couple has more or less children. Though in the extreme cases, where a couple has 5 or more children all couples said they were of excellent relationship quality or good relationship quality.

In Part 8, bar plots detail how couples meet. From the plot we see that a substantial amount of people meet in other, which could mean many people meet online. Other than the other group, people tend to meet their partners at work, where two people would have the same interests, school, where two people would potentially have the same motivation for education, and bar or nightclubs, meaning two people who both like to go out.

In the next part, the tables and bar plots illustrate the difference between where older and younger couples meet. The plots suggest that older genderations tend to meet more often at bars and or night clubs han younger couples. Younger couples on the other hand were more likely to meet at school than older couples.

Five males who exclusively liked other males were in relationships with females and one female who exclusively liked the other gender was dating a female. Only three of the males had responses to whether him and his partner broke up. Of these couples where the subject was exclusively attracted to the opposite gender of their partner, 50 percent of these relationships resulted in a breakup. While this breakup rate is significianlty higher than the average breakup rate, since the sample size is that of 4 responses, it is impossible to know if this result would carry over a larger sample.

The next table details people who were mostly attracted to a specific sex and were dating the gender they were less attracted to. Twenty-three precent of people in this group ended up breaking up which is a higher percent than the general population, but looking at the 95% confidence inteveral for this group, the mean of the general population falls within the groups interval. Thus, there is not a significant difference between the groups breakup rate and the general populations breakup rate.

The first question I asked about this data is if different religions had an impact on the likelihood of a breakup. Looking at the mosaic plot of different religions versus whether a couple would break up or not, it appears that religions does not seems to have an affect over whether couples break up or not.

Another question about the data, is if that if there is a difference amongst parental approval of straight couples versus homosexual couples. To see if there is indeed a difference, we look at a table of parental approval versus whether the person is in a homosexual relationship. In the table, the odds that a person has parental approval in a straight relationship is 2.067 times that of someone in a homosexual relationship.

Another question relevant to this dataset is whether couples meeting for the first time are more or less likely to result in a breakup or have a marriage than couples who did not meet online. To see this, we create a table and measure the odds of both respective events. The odds a couple that did not meet in person breaks up is .429 times that of a couple that met online. The odds a couple that did not meet there partner online marries their partner is .757 times that of a couple where the partners met online. From these results it seems that while relationships online had a higher tendency to break up, the fact couples who met online had a higher marriage rate tends to suggest that people who meet online are much more serious about starting long term relationships than people who meet in other ways.
